# n8n → Code Engine Migration — Full Implementation Plan

## Goal
Replace the self-hosted n8n automation engine with native Supabase Edge Functions (the "Code Engine"), without disrupting the ~30 existing users or any new users. The migration is invisible — users see zero UI changes.

---

## Architecture: Split Function Design

Instead of one monolithic `execute-automation` function, we split into **a master router + 3 trigger-specific executors**. This keeps each function small, testable, and independently deployable.

```mermaid
graph TD
    WM["webhook-meta<br/>(entry point)"] -->|use_code_engine = true| Router["execute-automation<br/>(master router)"]
    WM -->|use_code_engine = false| N8N["n8n (legacy)"]
    
    Router -->|post_comment| EPC["execute-post-comment<br/>• Reply to comment<br/>• Send DM with buttons<br/>• Carousel cards<br/>• Follow-to-unlock"]
    Router -->|user_dm / story_reply| EDM["execute-dm<br/>• Text DM reply<br/>• Template messages<br/>• Menu flow / postbacks<br/>• Lead Manager state machine"]
    Router -->|story_reply| ESR["execute-story<br/>• Story reply handling<br/>• DM follow-up"]
```

### Why split?

| Concern | Monolith | Split |
|---------|----------|-------|
| **Memory** | One function loads ALL logic (carousel builder, state machine, comment reply) | Each function loads only what it needs |
| **Testing** | Must test everything together | Test comment flow independently of DM flow |
| **Deploy risk** | Bug in DM logic breaks comment flows | Isolated blast radius |
| **Cold start** | Larger bundle = slower cold start | Smaller bundles = faster |
| **Readability** | 500+ line file | ~150 lines each, focused |

