## Phase 4: Update `create-workflow` (Skip n8n for Code Engine Users)

**Goal**: When a Code Engine user saves an automation, don't push anything to n8n.

### Changes

#### [MODIFY] [create-workflow/index.ts](file:///c:/QuickRevert/app.quickrevert.tech/supabase/functions/create-workflow/index.ts)

Add an early check after fetching `user_limits`:

```typescript
// Check if user uses Code Engine
const { data: userFlags } = await supabase
    .from('user_limits')
    .select('use_code_engine')
    .eq('user_id', userId)
    .maybeSingle();

if (userFlags?.use_code_engine) {
    // Code Engine user — no n8n workflow needed
    // Just ensure route tables are populated for webhook-meta routing
    await ensureRoutes(supabase, automationData, instagramAccount, automationId, account_id);
    
    return new Response(JSON.stringify({
        success: true,
        workflowId: 'code-engine',
        message: 'Automation saved (Code Engine)'
    }), { headers: { ...corsHeaders, 'Content-Type': 'application/json' } });
}

// ... rest of existing n8n logic unchanged ...
```

#### [MODIFY] `activate-workflow`, `deactivate-workflow`, `delete-workflow`

Same pattern — check flag, if Code Engine user, just update the `automations.status` column directly instead of calling n8n API.

#### [MODIFY] [n8nService.ts](file:///c:/QuickRevert/app.quickrevert.tech/src/lib/n8nService.ts)

No changes needed! The frontend still calls `create-workflow`, `activate-workflow`, etc. — the edge functions themselves decide whether to talk to n8n or not. The frontend is completely unaware of the engine switch.

